# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: arenga-pinnata
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] An **alcoholic beverage** (also called an **alcoholic drink** or **strong drink**) is any drink that contains alcohol, a central nervous system depressant.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] They are typically divided into three classes: beers, wines, and spirits; with alcohol content typically between 3% and 50%.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] The exact amount on which a beverage is considered alcoholic differs by country, with some considering drinks containing less than 0.5% to be non-alcoholic.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] These beverages are primarily consumed for the psychoactive effects that they produce.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Many societies have a distinct drinking culture, in which alcoholic drinks are integrated into parties.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Most countries have laws regulating the production, sale, and consumption of alcoholic beverages.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Some regulations require the labeling of the percentage alcohol content (as ABV or proof) and the use of a warning label.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Some countries ban the consumption of alcoholic drinks, but they are legal in most parts of the world.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] The temperance movement advocates against the consumption of alcoholic beverages.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] The global alcoholic drink industry exceeded $1.5 trillion in 2017.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Alcohol is one of the most widely used recreational drugs in the world, and about 33% of all humans currently drink alcohol.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] In 2015, among Americans, 86% of adults had consumed alcohol at some point, with 70% drinking it in the last year and 56% in the last month.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Several other animals are affected by alcohol similarly to humans and, once they consume it, will consume it again if given the opportunity; however, humans are the only species known to produce alcoholic drinks intentionally.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Alcohol is a depressant, a class of psychoactive drug that slows down activity in the central nervous system.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] In low doses it causes euphoria, reduces anxiety, and increases sociability.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] In higher doses, it causes drunkenness, stupor, unconsciousness, or death (an overdose).
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Long-term use can lead to alcoholism, an increased risk of developing several types of cancer, cardiovascular disease, and physical dependence.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Alcohol is classified as a group 1 carcinogen.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Discovery of late Stone Age jugs suggests that intentionally fermented drinks existed at least as early as the Neolithic period.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] The oldest verifiable brewery has been found in a prehistoric burial site in a cave near Haifa in modern-day Israel.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Researchers have found residue of 13,000-year-old beer that they think might have been used for ritual feasts to honor the dead.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] The traces of a wheat-and-barley-based alcohol were found in stone mortars carved into the cave floor.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] The Carmona Wine Urn is a first century Roman glass urn containing intact wine.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Beer was likely brewed from barley as early as 13,000 years ago in the Middle East.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Pliny the Elder wrote about the *golden age* of winemaking in Rome, the 2nd century BCE (200–100 BCE), when vineyards were planted.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Examination and analysis of ancient pottery jars from the neolithic village of Jiahu in the Henan province of northern China revealed residue left behind by the alcoholic drinks they had once contained.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Chemical analysis of the residue confirmed that a fermented drink made of grape and hawthorn fruit wine, honey mead and rice beer was being produced in 7000–5600 BC.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] The residence in which the jar was discovered and other houses in the same village were found to contain many such jars suggesting that wine was an important part of their diet.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] The earliest evidence of winemaking was dated at 6,000 to 5,800 BCE in Georgia in the South Caucasus.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Excavations surrounding Neolithic settlements there unearthed grape pips of a variety which differed from those of wild grapes, pointing to deliberate cultivation, and local pottery dated to approximately 6000 BCE was decorated with depictions of celebrating human figures.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] The earliest clear chemical evidence of beer produced from barley dates to about 3500–3100 BCE, from the site of Godin Tepe in the Zagros Mountains of western Iran.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] At a site dating to 3100-2900 BCE, a pottery vessel containing residue of alcoholic barley was discovered, possibly serving as the earliest proof of beer brewing in the region.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] However, it is unclear whether it was meant for intoxication or nourishment.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Celtic people were known to have been making types of alcoholic cider as early as 3000 BCE. and wine was consumed in Classical Greece at breakfast or at symposia, and in the 1st century BCE.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Archaeological finds as well as ancient documentation serve as testimony to the popularity and abundance of alcohol in the Sumerian society.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Access to alcohol was regulated, the social elite indulged in it and it served as sacrificial offerings to the gods.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] In Sumerian culture Alcohol was also a means for happiness.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] In the epic of Gilgamesh, Enkidu the wild man drinks seven jugs of beer, becomes elated and sings with joy.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Other characters routinely drink water, but drink alcohol when celebrating.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] During the new year celebrations, the ceremonial reenactment of the drunken union between the king of Uruk and the high priestess of Ishtar, the goddess of procreation, symbolized the genesis of Ninkasi, the beer goddess.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] A hymn to Ninkasi gives a detailed description of hash production in Sumer, involving the fermentation of bread and the addition of grapes and honey, resulting in an unfiltered brew drunk through straws.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] In Hierakonpolis, Egypt, the remains of a brewery dating to circa 3400 BCE was unearthed, with an estimated yield of up to 1135 litres (300 US gallons) of brew per day.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Wine was a symbol of power and was imported from abroad, hence it was reserved for royalty and the social elite, while beer was the drink of common society.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] In the tomb of the Scorpion king, who ruled Hierakonpolis when the brewery was built, approximately 700 wine jars imported from the southern Levant were unearthed.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Financial documents recorded that the daily ration of beer for the workers who built the pyramids of Giza was nearly 4 litres, and modern reproductions of the ancient recipe produced a brew weighed in at 5 percent ABV, the same as that of the modern day pint.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Despite the many Egyptian sources describing brewing methods, very few discuss intoxication.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] In honor of this deed a red coloured alcohol was drunk in large quantities during the festival causing similar intoxicated stupors.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Osiris was also associated with wine, as his death and resurrection were compared to the cycle of withering and regrowth of the vine during the winter and spring.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Multiple amphorae were discovered in the graves of pharaohs and elites as provisions for the afterlife and as offerings to Osiris, commonly with labels detailing their origin, maker, and date.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Over time, labels eventually included assessments of quality as well, such as "good," (*nfr*) "very good," (*nfr nfr*) or "very very good," (*nfr nfr nfr*) alongside provenance, and it was believed that certain vintages improved with age.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Archaeological findings reveal that some wines buried with their owners were several decades old, exceeding the average life expectancy, and therefore assumed to have outlived their creators.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Medieval Muslim chemists such as Jābir ibn Ḥayyān (Latin: Geber, ninth century) and Abū Bakr al-Rāzī (Latin: Rhazes, c.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] 865–925) experimented extensively with the distillation of various substances.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] The distillation of wine is attested in Arabic works attributed to al-Kindī (c.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] 872–950), and in the 28th book of al-Zahrāwī's (Latin: Abulcasis, 936–1013) *Kitāb al-Taṣrīf* (later translated into Latin as *Liber servatoris*).
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] 12th century: The process of distillation spread from the Middle East to Italy, where distilled alcoholic drinks were recorded in the mid-12th century.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] In Italy, the works of Taddeo Alderotti (1223–1296) describe a method for concentrating alcohol involving repeated fractional distillation through a water-cooled still.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] By the early 14th century, distilled alcoholic drinks had spread throughout the European continent.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Distillation spread to Ireland and Scotland no later than the 15th century, as did the common European practice of distilling "aqua vitae", primarily for medicinal purposes.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Drinking hard liquor was common occurrence in early nineteenth-century United States.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] The Whiskey Rebellion (also known as the Whiskey Insurrection) was a violent tax protest in the United States beginning in 1791 and ending in 1794 during the presidency of George Washington.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] The so-called "whiskey tax" was the first tax imposed on a domestic product by the newly formed federal government.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Beer was difficult to transport and spoiled more easily than rum and whiskey.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] The Rum Rebellion of 1808 was a *coup d'état* in the then-British penal colony of New South Wales, staged by the New South Wales Corps in order to depose Governor William Bligh.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Australia's first and only military coup, its name derives from the illicit rum trade of early Sydney, over which the 'Rum Corps', as it became known, maintained a monopoly.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] During the first half of the 19th century, it was widely referred to in Australia as the Great Rebellion.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] The alcohol monopoly system has a long history in various countries, often implemented to limit the availability and consumption of alcohol for public health and social welfare reasons.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] The alcohol monopoly was created in the Swedish town of Falun in 1850, to prevent overconsumption and reduce the profit motive for sales of alcohol.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] It later went all over the country in 1905 when the Swedish parliament ordered all sales of vodka to be done via local alcohol monopolies.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] In 1894, the Russian Empire established a state monopoly on vodka, which became a major source of revenue for the Russian government.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Beer is a beverage fermented from grain mash.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] It is typically made from barley or a blend of several grains and flavored with hops.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Most beer is naturally carbonated as part of the fermentation process.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] If the fermented mash is distilled, then the drink becomes a spirit.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Beer is the most consumed alcoholic beverage in the world.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Cider or cyder (/ˈsaɪdər/ *SY-dər*) is a fermented alcoholic drink made from any fruit juice; apple juice (traditional and most common), peaches, pears ("Perry" cider) or other fruit.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Cider alcohol content varies from 1.2% ABV to 8.5% or more in traditional English ciders.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] In some regions, cider may be called "apple wine".
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Fermented water is an ethanol-based water solution with approximately 15-17% ABV without sweet reserve.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Fermented water is exclusively fermented with white sugar, yeast, and water.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Fermented water is clarified after the fermentation to produce a colorless or off-white liquid with no discernible taste other than that of ethanol.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Mead (/miːd/), also called hydromel, is an alcoholic drink made by fermenting honey with water, sometimes with various fruits, spices, grains, or hops.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] The alcoholic content of mead may range from as low as 3% ABV to more than 20%.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] The defining characteristic of mead is that the majority of the drink's fermentable sugar is derived from honey.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Pulque is the Mesoamerican fermented drink made from the "honey water" of maguey, *Agave americana*.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Pulque can be distilled to produce tequila or Mezcal.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Rice wine is an alcoholic drink fermented and possibly distilled from rice, consumed in East Asia, Southeast Asia and South Asia.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Sake, huangjiu, mijiu, and cheongju are popular examples of East Asian rice wine.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Wine is a fermented beverage most commonly produced from grapes.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Wine involves a longer fermentation process than beer and often a long aging process (months or years), resulting in an alcohol content of 9%–16% ABV.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Sparkling wines such as French Champagne, Catalan Cava and Italian Prosecco are also made from grapes, with a secondary fermentation.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Fruit wines are made from fruits other than grapes, such as plums, cherries, or apples.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Wine, beer, and spirits are produced through the activity of yeasts, a group of roughly 160 species of single-celled fungi, some of which are beneficial, while others are associated with food spoilage or human disease.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] The most commonly used yeasts in fermentation and baking belong to the genus *Saccharomyces*, whose name means "sugar fungus".
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] These organisms are cultivated both for their role in generating flavors and aromas considered desirable, and for their ability to inhibit the growth of competing microbes which would otherwise infect food.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Their production of alcohol is linked to their capacity to function with minimal oxygen.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Distilled beverages (also called liquors or spirit drinks) are alcoholic drinks produced by distilling (i.e., concentrating by distillation) ethanol produced by means of fermenting grain, fruit, or vegetables.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Unsweetened, distilled, alcoholic drinks that have an alcohol content of at least 20% ABV are called *spirits*.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] For the most common distilled drinks, such as whisky (or whiskey) and vodka, the alcohol content is around 40%.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] The term *hard liquor* is used in North America to distinguish distilled drinks from undistilled ones (implicitly weaker).
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Brandy, gin, mezcal, rum, tequila, vodka, whisky (or whiskey), baijiu, shōchū and soju are examples of distilled drinks.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Distilling concentrates the alcohol and eliminates some of the congeners.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Freeze distillation concentrates ethanol along with methanol and fusel alcohols (fermentation by-products partially removed by distillation) in applejack.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Fortified wine is wine, such as port or sherry, to which a distilled beverage (usually brandy) has been added.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Fortified wine is distinguished from spirits made from wine in that spirits are produced by means of distillation, while fortified wine is wine that has had a spirit added to it.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Many different styles of fortified wine have been developed, including port, sherry, madeira, marsala, commandaria, and the aromatized wine vermouth.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Rectified spirit, also called "neutral grain spirit", is alcohol which has been purified by means of "rectification" (i.e. repeated distillation).
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] The term *neutral* refers to the spirit's lack of flavor that would have been present if the mash ingredients had been distilled to a lower level of alcoholic purity.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Rectified spirit also lacks any flavoring added to it after distillation (as is done, for example, with gin).
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Other kinds of spirits, such as whiskey, (or whisky) are distilled to a lower alcohol percentage to preserve the flavor of the mash.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Rectified spirit is a clear, colorless, flammable liquid that may contain as much as 95% ABV.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] It is often used for medicinal purposes.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] It may be a grain spirit, or it may be made from other plants.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] It is used in mixed drinks, liqueurs, and tinctures, and also as a household solvent.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] In the alcoholic drinks industry, congeners are substances produced during fermentation.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] These substances include small amounts of chemicals such as occasionally desired alcohols, like propanol and 3-methyl-1-butanol, as well as compounds that are never desired such as acetone, acetaldehyde and glycols.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Congeners are responsible for most of the taste and aroma of distilled alcoholic drinks and contribute to the taste of non-distilled drinks.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] It has been suggested that these substances contribute to the symptoms of a hangover.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Tannins are congeners found in wine in the presence of phenolic compounds.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Wine tannins add bitterness, have a drying sensation, taste herbaceous, and are often described as astringent.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Wine tannins add balance, complexity, structure and make a wine last longer, so they play an important role in the aging of wine.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Top-shelf liquor (or "premium liquor") is a term used in marketing to describe higher-priced alcoholic beverages, typically stored on the top shelves within bars.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] A mixed drink is a beverage in which two or more ingredients are mixed, and is often alcoholic.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Alcohol powder or powdered alcohol or dry alcohol is a product generally made using micro-encapsulation.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] When reconstituted with water, the powder becomes an alcoholic drink.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] A well drink or rail drink is an alcoholic beverage or mixed drink made using the lower-cost liquors stored within easy reach of the bartender in the bar's "speed rail", "speed rack", or "well", a rack or shelf at a lower level than the bar that the bartender uses to prepare drinks.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] The average number of people who drink as of 2016 was 39% for males and 25% for females (2.4 billion people in total).
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Females on average drink 0.7 drinks per day while males drink 1.7 drinks per day.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] The rates of drinking varies significantly in different areas of the world.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Drinking games are games which involve the consumption of alcoholic beverages and often enduring the subsequent intoxication resulting from them.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Evidence of the existence of drinking games dates back to antiquity.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Drinking games have been banned at some institutions, particularly colleges and universities.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] A drinking song is a song sung while drinking an alcoholic beverage.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] A beer garden (German: *Biergarten*) is an outdoor area in which beer and food are served, typically at shared tables shaded by trees.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] A beer hall (German: *Bierpalast, Bierhalle*) is a large pub that specializes in beer.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] A cider house is an establishment that sells alcoholic cider for consumption on the premises.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Some cider houses also sell cider "to go", for consumption off the premises.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] A traditional cider house was often little more than a room in a farmhouse or cottage, selling locally fermented cider.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] An ouzeri (Greek *ουζερί* IPA: [uzeˈri]) is a type of Greek tavern which serves ouzo (a Greek liquor) and mezedes (small finger foods).
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Pulquerías (or pulcherías) are a type of tavern in Mexico that specialize in serving an alcoholic beverage known as pulque.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] A tiki bar is a themed drinking establishment that serves elaborate cocktails, especially rum-based mixed drinks such as the Mai Tai and Zombie cocktails.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Tiki bars are aesthetically defined by their tiki culture décor which is based upon a romanticized conception of tropical cultures, most commonly Polynesian.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] A toddy shop is a drinking establishment seen in some parts of India (particularly Kerala) where palm toddy, a mildly alcoholic beverage made from the sap of palm trees, is served along with food.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] A wine bar is a tavern-like business focusing on selling wine, rather than liquor or beer.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] A typical feature of many wine bars is a wide selection of wines available by the glass.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Some wine bars are profiled on wines of a certain type of origin, such as Italian wine or Champagne.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] While many wine bars are private "stand-alone" establishments, in some cases, wine bars are associated with a specific wine retailer or other outlet of wine, to provide additional marketing for that retailer's wine portfolio.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] In countries where licensing regulations allow this, some wine bars also sell the wines they serve, and effectively function as a hybrid between a wine shop and a wine bar.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] A beer festival is an event at which a variety of beers are available for purchase.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] There may be a theme, for instance beers from a particular area, or a particular brewing style such as winter ales.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Annual wine festivals celebrate viticulture and usually occur after the harvest of the grapes which, in the northern hemisphere, generally falls at the end of September and runs until well into October or later.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] They are common in most wine regions around the world and are to be considered in the tradition of other harvest festivals.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Beer tasting is a way to learn more about the history, ingredients, and production of beer, as well as different beer styles, hops, yeast, and beer presentation.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] A common approach is to analyze the appearance, smell, and taste of the beer, and then make a final judgment on the beer's quality.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] There are various scales used by beer journalists and experts to rate beer, such as the 1-20 scale used by British sommelier Jancis Robinson and the 1-100 scale used by American sommelier Joshua M.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Professional organizations like the Wine & Spirit Education Trust often rate beer using verbal grades ranging from "faulty" to "outstanding" on a 1-5 scale.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Wine tasting, on the other hand, is the sensory examination and evaluation of wine.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] While the practice of wine tasting is ancient, a more formalized methodology has been established since the 14th century.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Modern, professional wine tasters use specialized terminology to describe the range of perceived flavors, aromas, and general characteristics of a wine.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] More informal, recreational tasting may involve similar terminology, but with a less analytical process and a more general, personal appreciation of the wine.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Craft beer tourism refers to tourism where the primary motivation of travel is to visit a brewery, beer festival, beer related activity or other event that allows attendees to experience all aspects of the craft beer-making, consuming and purchasing process.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Enotourism, oenotourism, wine tourism, or **vinitourism** refers to tourism whose purpose is or includes the tasting, consumption or purchase of wine, often at or near the source.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Where other types of tourism are often passive in nature, enotourism can consist of visits to wineries, tasting wines, vineyard walks, or even taking an active part in the harvest.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] An apéritif is any alcoholic beverage usually served before a meal to stimulate the appetite, while a digestif is any alcoholic beverage served after a meal for the stated purpose of improving digestion.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Fortified wine, liqueurs, and dry champagne are common apéritifs.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Because apéritifs are served before dining, they are usually dry rather than sweet.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] One example is Cinzano, a brand of vermouth.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Digestifs include brandy, fortified wines and herb-infused spirits (Drambuie).
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Pure ethanol tastes bitter to humans; some people also describe it as sweet.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] However, ethanol is also a moderately effective solvent for many fatty substances and essential oils.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] This facilitates the use of flavoring and coloring compounds in alcoholic drinks as a taste mask, especially in distilled drinks.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Some flavors may be naturally present in the beverage's raw material.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Beer and wine may also be flavored before fermentation, and spirits may be flavored before, during, or after distillation.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Sometimes flavor is obtained by allowing the beverage to stand for months or years in oak barrels, usually made of American or French oak.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] A few brands of spirits may also have fruit or herbs inserted into the bottle at the time of bottling.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Wine is important in cuisine not just for its value as an accompanying beverage, but as a flavor agent, primarily in stocks and braising, since its acidity lends balance to rich savory or sweet dishes.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Wine sauce is an example of a culinary sauce that uses wine as a primary ingredient.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Natural wines may exhibit a broad range of alcohol content, from below 9% to above 16% ABV, with most wines being in the 12.5–14.5% range.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Fortified wines (usually with brandy) may contain 20% alcohol or more.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Vinegar (*vyn egre*; sour wine) is an aqueous solution of acetic acid and trace compounds that may include flavorings.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Vinegar typically contains from 5% to 18% acetic acid by volume.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Usually, the acetic acid is produced by a double fermentation, converting simple sugars to ethanol using yeast and ethanol to acetic acid using acetic acid bacteria.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Wine and food matching is the process of pairing food dishes with wine to enhance the dining experience.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] In many cultures, wine has had a long history of being a staple at the dinner table and in some ways both the winemaking and culinary traditions of a region will have evolved together over the years.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Rather than following a set of rules, local cuisines were paired simply with local wines.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] The modern "art" of food pairings is a relatively recent phenomenon, fostering an industry of books and media with guidelines for pairings of particular foods and wine.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] In the restaurant industry, sommeliers are often present to make food pairing recommendations for the guest.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] The main concept behind pairings is that certain elements (such as texture and flavor) in both food and wine interact with each other, and thus finding the right combination of these elements will make the entire dining experience more enjoyable.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] However, taste and enjoyment are very subjective and what may be a "textbook perfect" pairing for one taster could be less enjoyable to another.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Alcoholic beverages are typical offerings for the folk saint Maximón, and Santa Muerte.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Both folk saints have been described as narco-saints.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] A libation is a ritual pouring of a liquid, or grains such as rice, as an offering to a deity or spirit, or in memory of the dead.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] It was common in many religions of antiquity and continues to be offered in cultures today.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Wine or other alcoholic drinks are often used for libation.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Libation was part of ancient Egyptian society where it was a drink offering to honor and please the various divinities, sacred ancestors, humans present and humans who are alive but not physically present, as well as the environment.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] It is suggested that libation originated somewhere in the upper Nile Valley and spread out to other regions of Africa and the world.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] In the Quechua and Aymara cultures of the South American Andes, it is common to pour a small amount of one's beverage on the ground before drinking as an offering to the Pachamama, or Mother Earth.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] This especially holds true when drinking Chicha, an alcoholic beverage unique to this part of the world.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] The libation ritual is commonly called *challa* and is performed quite often, usually before meals and during celebrations.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] The amount of sacramental wine consumed during the Eucharist is typically limited to a single sip or small portion, which does not result in a measurable increase in the participant's blood alcohol content.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] This controlled and symbolic consumption of the sacramental wine is an integral part of the Eucharistic rite and does not lead to intoxication.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] According to the Catholic Church, the sacramental wine used in the Eucharist must contain alcohol.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Some Evangelical Lutheran Church in America (ELCA) congregations make grape juice available for children and those who are abstaining from alcohol and some will accommodate those with an allergy to wheat, gluten, or grapes.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] A tincture is typically an extract of plant or animal material dissolved in ethanol (ethyl alcohol).
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Solvent concentrations of 25–60% are common, but may run as high as 90%.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] In chemistry, a tincture is a solution that has ethanol as its solvent.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] In herbal medicine, alcoholic tinctures are made with various ethanol concentrations, which should be at least 20% alcohol for preservation purposes.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] A flaming drink is often ignited for aesthetic and entertainment purposes.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Alcoholic beverage may be consumed to celebrate observances such as the International Beer Day, International whisk(e)y day, or National Vodka Day.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] They also drink them for social events like International Women's Collaboration Brew Day, where people come together to make beer.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Alcohol measurements are units of measurement for determining amounts of beverage alcohol.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Alcohol concentration in beverages is commonly expressed as alcohol by volume (ABV), ranging from less than 0.1% in fruit juices to up to 98% in rare cases of spirits.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] A standard drink is used globally to quantify alcohol intake, though its definition varies widely by country.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Serving sizes of alcoholic beverages also vary by country.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Alcohol laws regulate the manufacture, packaging, labelling, distribution, sale, consumption, blood alcohol content of motor vehicle drivers, open containers, and transportation of alcoholic drinks.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Such laws generally seek to reduce the adverse health and social impacts of alcohol consumption.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] In particular, alcohol laws set the legal drinking age, which usually varies between 15 and 21 years old, sometimes depending upon the type of alcoholic drink (e.g., beer vs wine vs hard liquor or distillates).
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Some countries do not have a legal drinking or purchasing age, but most countries set the minimum age at 18 years.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Some countries, such as the U.S., have the drinking age higher than the legal age of majority (18), at age 21 in all 50 states.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Such laws may take the form of permitting distribution only to licensed stores, monopoly stores, or pubs and they are often combined with taxation, which serves to reduce the demand for alcohol (by raising its price) and it is a form of revenue for governments.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] These laws also often limit the hours or days (e.g., "blue laws") on which alcohol may be sold or served, as can also be seen in the "last call" ritual in US and Canadian bars, where bartenders and servers ask patrons to place their last orders for alcohol, due to serving hour cutoff laws.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] In some countries, alcohol cannot be sold to a person who is already intoxicated.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Alcohol laws in many countries prohibit drunk driving.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] In some jurisdictions, alcoholic drinks are totally prohibited for reasons of religion (e.g., Islamic countries with sharia law) or for reasons of local option, public health, and morals (e.g., Prohibition in the United States from 1920 to 1933).
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] In jurisdictions which enforce sharia law, the consumption of alcoholic drinks is an illegal offense, although such laws may exempt non-Muslims.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Alcohol is used in rum-running, the illegal business of smuggling alcoholic beverages where such transportation is forbidden by law.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Wine fraud relates to the commercial aspects of wine.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] The most prevalent type of fraud is one where wines are adulterated, usually with the addition of cheaper products (e.g. juices) and sometimes with harmful chemicals and sweeteners (compensating for color or flavor).
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Moonshine is illegal to produce and sell in most countries.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] In Prohibition-era United States, moonshine distillation was done at night to deter discovery.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Once the liquor was distilled, drivers called "runners" or "bootleggers" smuggled moonshine liquor across the region in cars specially modified for speed and load-carrying capacity.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Outbreaks of methanol poisoning have occurred when methanol is used to adulterate moonshine.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] In Australia, a sly-grog shop (or shanty) is an unlicensed hotel, liquor-store or other vendor of alcoholic beverages, sometimes with the added connotation of selling poor-quality products.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Pruno also known as prison hooch or prison wine, is a term used in the United States to describe an improvised alcoholic beverage.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] It is variously made from apples, oranges, fruit cocktail, fruit juices, hard candy, sugar, high fructose syrup, and possibly other ingredients, including crumbled bread.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Most countries have laws specifically for the offense of drunk driving.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Driving under the influence (DUI) or driving while intoxicated (DWI), is the crime of driving a motor vehicle while impaired by alcohol or other drugs (including those prescribed by physicians).
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Public intoxication laws vary widely by jurisdiction, but include public nuisance laws, open-container laws, and prohibitions on drinking alcohol in public or certain areas.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Alcohol is a common metabolic by-product formed during the breakdown of sugars in many living cells, though it is typically further metabolised to release additional energy.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Certain yeasts constitute an exception, as they excrete alcohol into their environment, where it acts as a chemical defense against competing microorganisms; this role is analogous to that of lactic acid in fermented foods and aromatic compounds in plants.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] While advantageous to yeast, alcohol is toxic to most cells, and in humans its intoxicating effects result from interference with the normal functioning of brain cells.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Alcohol is a depressant, which in low doses causes euphoria, reduces anxiety, and increases sociability.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] In higher doses, it causes drunkenness, stupor, unconsciousness, or death.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] A meta analysis of 107 cohort studies concludes low daily alcohol intake provides no health benefits and increased consumption, even at relatively low levels of daily intake (>2 beverages for women and >3 beverages for men), increases health- and mortality-risks.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Short-term effects of alcohol consumption range from a decrease in anxiety and motor skills and euphoria at lower doses to intoxication (drunkenness), to stupor, unconsciousness, anterograde amnesia (memory "blackouts"), and central nervous system depression at higher doses.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Cell membranes are highly permeable to alcohol, so once it is in the bloodstream, it can diffuse into nearly every cell in the body.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Alcohol can greatly exacerbate sleep problems.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] During abstinence, residual disruptions in sleep regularity and sleep patterns are the greatest predictors of relapse.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Long-term use can lead to an alcohol use disorder, an increased risk of developing physical dependence, cardiovascular disease, and several types of cancer.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Some nations have introduced alcohol packaging warning messages that inform consumers about alcohol and cancer, as well as fetal alcohol syndrome.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] The addition of warning labels on alcoholic beverages is historically supported by organizations of the temperance movement, such as the Woman's Christian Temperance Union, as well as by medical organisations, such as the Irish Cancer Society.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] WHO estimates nearly half of alcohol-attributable cancers in the WHO European Region are linked to light or moderate drinking defined as "less than 1.5 litres of wine or less than 3.5 litres of beer or less than 450 millilitres of spirits per week".
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Public awareness of the link between alcohol consumption and cancer is low in the U.S.
[src:arenga-pinnata/alcoholic-drink] Surgeon General argued for the use of cancer warning labels on alcohol products.
[src:arenga-pinnata/allen-press] It was the publisher, amongst others, of the *Journal of Parasitology* (American Society of Parasitologists), *Phycologia* (International Phycological Society), and the *Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington* (Biological Society of Washington).
[src:arenga-pinnata/allen-press] Many of the DOIs generated by Allen Press no longer work.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The **Arecaceae** (/ˌærəˈkeɪsi.iː, -ˌaɪ/) are a family of perennial, flowering plants in the monocot order Arecales.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Their growth form can be climbers, shrubs, tree-like and stemless plants, all commonly known as **palms**.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Those having a tree-like form are colloquially called **palm trees**.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Currently, 181 genera with around 2,600 species are known, most of which are restricted to tropical and subtropical climates.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Most palms are distinguished by their large, compound, evergreen leaves, known as fronds, arranged at the top of an unbranched stem, except for the *Hyphaene* genus, which has branched palms.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] However, palms exhibit an enormous diversity in physical characteristics and inhabit nearly every type of habitat within their range, from rainforests to deserts.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Palms are among the best known and most extensively cultivated plant families.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] They have been important to humans throughout much of history, especially in regions like the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] A wide range of common products and foods are derived from palms.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] In contemporary times, palms are also widely used in landscaping.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] In many historical cultures, because of their importance as food, palms were symbols for such ideas as victory, peace, and fertility.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The word *Arecaceae* is derived from the word *areca* with the suffix "-aceae".
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] *Areca* is derived, via Portuguese, from Malayalam അടയ്ക്ക (*aṭaykka*), which comes in turn from Dravidian **aṭ-ay-kkāy* ("areca nut").
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The suffix *-aceae* is the feminine plural of the Latin *-āceus* ("resembling").
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Whether as shrubs, tree-like, or vines, palms have two methods of growth: solitary or clustered.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The common representation is that of a solitary shoot ending in a crown of leaves.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] This monopodial character may be exhibited by prostrate, trunkless, and trunk-forming members.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Some common palms restricted to solitary growth include *Washingtonia* and *Roystonea*.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Palms may instead grow in sparse though dense clusters.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The trunk develops an axillary bud at a leaf node, usually near the base, from which a new shoot emerges.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The new shoot, in turn, produces an axillary bud and a clustering habit results.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Exclusively sympodial genera include many of the rattans, *Guihaia*, and *Rhapis*.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Several palm genera have both solitary and clustering members.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Palms which are usually solitary may grow in clusters and vice versa.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Palms have large, evergreen leaves that are either palmately ('fan-leaved') or pinnately ('feather-leaved') compound and spirally (-alternately) arranged at the top of the stem, with the sole exception of the king raphia (*Raphia vinifera* variety *nigerica*) which has opposite pairs of fronds.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The leaves have a tubular sheath at the base that usually splits open on one side at maturity.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The inflorescence is a spadix or spike surrounded by one or more bracts or spathes that become woody at maturity.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The flowers are generally small and white, radially symmetric, and can be either uni- or bisexual.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The sepals and petals usually number three each and may be distinct or joined at the base.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The stamens generally number six, with filaments that may be separate, attached to each other, or attached to the pistil at the base.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The fruit is usually a single-seeded drupe (sometimes berry-like) but some genera (e.g., *Salacca*) may contain two or more seeds in each fruit.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Like all monocots, palms do not have the ability to increase the width of a stem (secondary growth) via the same kind of vascular cambium found in non-monocot woody plants.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] This explains the cylindrical shape of the trunk (almost constant diameter) that is often seen in palms, unlike in ring-forming trees.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] However, many palms, like some other monocots, do have secondary growth, although because it does not arise from a single vascular cambium producing xylem inwards and phloem outwards, it is often called "anomalous secondary growth".
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The Arecaceae are notable among monocots for their height, and for the size of their seeds, leaves, and inflorescences.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] *Ceroxylon quindiuense*, Colombia's national "tree", is the tallest monocot in the world, reaching up to 60 metres (197 ft) tall.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The *coco de mer* (*Lodoicea maldivica*) has the largest seeds of any plant, 40–50 centimetres (16–20 in) in diameter and weighing 15–30 kilograms (33–66 lb) each (coconuts are the second largest).
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Raffia palms (*Raphia* spp.) have the largest leaves of any plant, up to 25 metres (82 ft) long and 3 metres (10 ft) wide.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The *Corypha* species have the largest inflorescence of any plant, up to 7.5 metres (25 ft) tall and containing millions of small flowers.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] *Calamus* stems can reach 200 metres (656 ft) in length.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Most palms are native to tropical and subtropical climates.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Palms thrive in moist and hot climates but can be found in a variety of different habitats.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Their diversity is highest in wet, lowland forests.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] South America, the Caribbean, and areas of the South Pacific and southern Asia are regions of concentration.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Colombia may have the highest number of palm species in one country.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] There are some palms that are also native to desert areas such as the Arabian Peninsula and parts of northwestern Mexico.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Only about 130 palm species naturally grow entirely beyond the tropics, mostly in humid lowland subtropical climates, in highlands in southern Asia, and along the rim lands of the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The northernmost native palm is *Chamaerops humilis*, which reaches 44°N latitude along the coast of Liguria, Italy.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] In the southern hemisphere, the southernmost palm is the *Rhopalostylis sapida* (nīkau), which reaches 44°S on the Chatham Islands where an oceanic climate prevails.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Cultivation of palms is possible north of subtropical climates, and some higher latitude locales such as the British Isles and the Pacific Northwest feature a few palms in protected locations and microclimates.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] In the United States, there are at least 12 native palm species, mostly occurring in the states of the Deep South and Florida.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] More than two-thirds of palm species live in humid moist forests, where some species grow tall enough to form part of the canopy and shorter ones form part of the understory.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Some species form pure stands in areas with poor drainage or regular flooding, including *Raphia hookeri* which is common in coastal freshwater swamps in West Africa.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Other palms live in tropical mountain habitats above 1 thousand metres (3 thousand feet), such as those in the genus *Ceroxylon* native to the Andes.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Palms may also live in grasslands and scrublands, usually associated with a water source, and in desert oases such as the date palm.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] A few palms are adapted to extremely basic lime soils, while others are similarly adapted to extreme potassium deficiency and toxicity of heavy metals in serpentine soils.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Palms are a monophyletic group of plants, meaning the group consists of a common ancestor and all its descendants.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Extensive taxonomic research on palms began with botanist H.E.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Moore, who organized palms into 15 major groups based mostly on general morphological characteristics.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The following classification, proposed by N.W.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Dransfield in 1987, is a revision of Moore's classification that organizes palms into 6 subfamilies.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] A few general traits of each subfamily are listed below.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The **Phytelephantoideae** is the sixth subfamily of Arecaceae in N.W.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Members of this group have distinct monopodial flower clusters.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Other distinct features include a gynoecium with five to 10 joined carpels, and flowers with more than three parts per whorl.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Fruits are multiple-seeded and have multiple parts.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] From the modern phylogenomic data, the Phytelephantoideae are tribe in the Ceroxyloideae subfamily.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Currently, few extensive phylogenetic studies of the Arecaceae exist.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] In 1997, Baker *et al.* explored subfamily and tribe relationships using chloroplast DNA from 60 genera from all subfamilies and tribes.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The results strongly showed the Calamoideae are monophyletic, and Ceroxyloideae and Coryphoideae are paraphyletic.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The relationships of Arecoideae are uncertain, but they are possibly related to the Ceroxyloideae and Phytelephantoideae.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] However, hybridization has been observed among *Orbignya* and *Phoenix* species, and using chloroplast DNA in cladistic studies may produce inaccurate results due to maternal inheritance of the chloroplast DNA.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Chemical and molecular data from non-organelle DNA, for example, could be more effective for studying palm phylogeny.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Recently, nuclear genomes and transcriptomes have been used to reconstruct the phylogeny of palms.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] This has revealed, for example, that a whole-genome duplication event occurred early in the evolution of the Arecaceae lineage, that was not experienced by its sister clade, the Dasypogonaceae.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] For a phylogenetic tree of the family, see the list of Arecaceae genera.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The Arecaceae were the first modern family of monocots to appear in the fossil record around 108 million years ago (Mya), during the Early Cretaceous period.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The first modern species, such as *Nypa fruticans* and *Acrocomia aculeata*, appeared 69 Mya, as evidenced by fossil *Nypa* pollen.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Palms appear to have undergone an early period of adaptive radiation.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] By 60 Mya, many of the modern, specialized genera of palms appeared and became widespread and common, much more widespread than their range today.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Because palms separated from the monocots earlier than other families, they developed more intrafamilial specialization and diversity.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] By tracing back these diverse characteristics of palms to the basic structures of monocots, palms may be valuable in studying monocot evolution.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Several species of palms have been identified from flowers preserved in amber, including *Palaeoraphe dominicana* and *Roystonea palaea*.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Fossil evidence of them can also be found in samples of petrified palmwood.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Evidence for cultivation of the date palm by Mesopotamians and other Middle Eastern peoples exists from more than 5,000 years ago, in the form of date wood, pits for storing dates, and other remains of the date palm in Mesopotamian sites.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The date palm had a significant effect on the history of the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] In the text "Date Palm Products" (1993), W.H.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] An indication of the importance of palms in ancient times is that they are mentioned more than 30 times in the Bible, and at least 22 times in the Quran.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Arecaceae have great economic importance, including coconut products, oils, dates, palm syrup, ivory nuts, carnauba wax, rattan cane, raffia, and palm wood.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] This family supplies a large amount of the human diet and several other human uses, both by absolute amount produced and by number of species domesticated.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] This is far higher than almost any other plant family, sixth out of domesticated crops in the human diet, and first in total economic value produced – sharing the top spot with the Poaceae and Fabaceae.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] These human uses have also spread many Arecaceae species around the world.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Like many other plants, palms have been threatened by human intervention and exploitation.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The greatest risk to palms is destruction of habitat, especially in the tropical forests, due to urbanization, wood-chipping, mining, and conversion to farmland.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Palms rarely reproduce after such great changes in the habitat, and those with small habitat ranges are most vulnerable to them.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The harvesting of heart of palm, a delicacy in salads, also poses a threat because it is derived from the palm's apical meristem, a vital part of the palm that cannot be regrown (except in domesticated varieties, e.g. of peach palm).
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The use of rattan palms in furniture has caused a major population decrease in these species that has negatively affected local and international markets, as well as biodiversity in the area.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The sale of seeds to nurseries and collectors is another threat, as the seeds of popular palms are sometimes harvested directly from the wild.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] In 2006, at least 100 palm species were considered endangered, and nine species have been reported as recently extinct.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] However, several factors make palm conservation more difficult.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Palms live in almost every type of warm habitat and have tremendous morphological diversity.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Most palm seeds lose viability quickly, and they cannot be preserved in low temperatures because the cold kills the embryo.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Using botanical gardens for conservation also presents problems, since they can rarely house more than a few plants of any species or truly imitate the natural setting.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] There is also the risk that cross-pollination can lead to hybrid species.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The Palm Specialist Group of the World Conservation Union (IUCN) began in 1984, and has performed a series of three studies to find basic information on the status of palms in the wild, use of wild palms, and palms under cultivation.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Two projects on palm conservation and use supported by the World Wildlife Fund took place from 1985 to 1990 and 1986–1991, in the American tropics and southeast Asia, respectively.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Both studies produced copious new data and publications on palms.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Preparation of a global action plan for palm conservation began in 1991, supported by the IUCN, and was published in 1996.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The rarest palm known is *Hyophorbe amaricaulis*.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The only living individual remains at the Botanic Gardens of Curepipe in Mauritius.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Some pests are specialists to particular taxa.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The palm branch was a symbol of triumph and victory in classical antiquity.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The Romans rewarded champions of the games and celebrated military successes with palm branches.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Early Christians used the palm branch to symbolize the victory of the faithful over enemies of the soul, as in the Palm Sunday festival celebrating the triumphal entry of Jesus Christ into Jerusalem.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] In Judaism, the palm represents peace and plenty, and is one of the Four Species of Sukkot; the palm may also symbolize the Tree of Life in Kabbalah.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] The canopies of the Rathayatra carts which carry the deities of Krishna and his family members in the cart festival of Jagganath Puri in India are marked with the emblem of a palm tree.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Specifically it is the symbol of Krishna's brother, Baladeva.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] In 1840, the American geologist Edward Hitchcock (1793–1864) published the first tree-like paleontology chart in his *Elementary Geology*, with two separate trees of life for the plants and the animals.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] These are crowned (graphically) with the Palms and with Man.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Today, the palm, especially the coconut palm, remains a symbol of the tropical island paradise.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecaceae] Palms appear on the flags and seals of several places where they are native, including those of Cuba, Haiti, Guam, Saudi Arabia, Florida, and South Carolina.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecales] The APG IV system of 2016 places Dasypogonaceae in this order, after studies showing Dasypogonaceae as sister to Arecaceae.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecales] However, this decision has been called into question.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecales] The Cronquist system of 1981 assigned the order to the subclass Arecidae in the class Liliopsida (= monocotyledons).
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecales] The Thorne system (1992) and the Dahlgren system assigned the order to the superorder Areciflorae, also called Arecanae in the subclass Liliidae (= monocotyledons), with the single family Arecaceae.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecales] This was unchanged from the APG system of 1998, although it used the spelling "commelinoids" instead of commelinids.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecales] In plant taxonomy, Principes is a botanical name, meaning "the first".
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecales] It was used in the Engler system for an order in the *Monocotyledones* and later in the Kubitzki system.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecales] This order included one family only, the *Palmae* (alternate name *Arecaceae*).
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecales] As the rules for botanical nomenclature provide for the use of such descriptive botanical names above the rank of family it is quite allowed to use this name even today, but in practice most systems prefer the name Arecales.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arecales] Following this, *Principes* became the name of the journal of the International Palm Society, becoming *Palms* in 1999.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] It is a medium-sized palm, growing to 20 metres (66 feet) tall, with the trunk remaining covered by the rough old leaf bases.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] The leaves are 6–12 m (20–39 ft) long and 1.5 m (5 ft) broad, pinnate, with the pinnae in 1–6 rows, 40–70 centimetres (16–28 inches) long and 5 cm (2 in) broad.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] The fruit is subglobose, 7 cm (3 in) diameter, green maturing black.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] The palm is remarkable in two ways; first it is fast growing.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] One at the conservatory of the New York Botanic Garden grew to a height of 27 m (89 ft) in 25 years.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] Secondly it has very long pseudo-spines which look dangerous, but are not; possibly an example of Batesian mimicry.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] It is not a threatened species, though it is locally rare in some parts of its range.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] It serves as an important part of the diet of several endangered species, including cloud rats of the genus *Phloeomys*.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] Many products of the palm are used, as food, as construction materials, and for other purposes.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] The sap is harvested for commercial use in southeast Asia, yielding a sugar known as *gur* in India, *gula aren* in Indonesia, and *pakaskas* in the Philippines.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] Edmund Roberts talks about drinking an alcoholic beverage made in the Cavite area.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] He described it as a "fermented" and "intoxicating liquor".
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] Sugar (jaggery) is also commonly derived from the fresh sap in Indonesia and the Philippines.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] These are traditionally prevented from fermenting by placing crushed chili or ginger in the collecting container.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] The sap is boiled until it reduces to a thick syrup which is then dried into a brown sugar.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] Similar sugar extraction methods are also traditionally used for other sugar palms, such as the buri palm (*Corypha elata*).
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] This crop may develop into a major resource of biofuel (ethanol).
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] The immature fruits are widely consumed in the Philippines (called *kaong*) and Indonesia (called *buah kolang-kaling* or *buah tap*) and are made into canned fruits after they are boiled in sugar syrup.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] The seeds can be used in many different recipes, such as sour soup, or eaten with pandan juice, syrup, or coconut milk.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] These seeds have a chewy and sweet flavor .Young seeds are soft and easy to chew.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] When the fruits are overripe, they will have a harder texture.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] The boiled water obtained from boiling fruits can also be utilized as a natural dye for fabrics.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] The fruit stalk can be cut it into smaller stick used as firewood.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] Some people also utilized it as part of furniture.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] In Thailand, some people eat the young shoot with chili sauce, and use them as cooking ingredients in dishes like soup.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] According to the study on bas-reliefs of Javanese ancient temples such as Borobudur, this type of roof is known in ancient Java vernacular architecture.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] It can be found today in Balinese temple roof architecture and Minangkabau Rumah Gadang *gonjong* horn-like curved roof architecture, such as those found in Pagaruyung Palace.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] In Thailand, fibres were once used to create raincoats for miners called *Jang Sui* (Thai: จั่งซุ้ย).
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] The cloth made of this plant has a rough texture, making it unsuitable for most clothing.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] The leaves as well as the leaf midribs can be used to weave baskets and marquetry work in furniture.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] In Indonesia, starch can also be extracted from sugar palms and used in place of rice flour in noodles, cakes, and other dishes.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] The timber is used for high grade construction, posts, beams, flooring, interior finish, wharf bridge building and other uses where strength and durability are important.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] The trunks are typically used for making tools and furniture.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] Weevils that live inside the trunk are sometimes collected as food by people harvesting the fruits.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] The seeds can be boiled and the stem tips can be eaten as vegetables.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] The young flower stalks can be bruised to obtain the juice.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] Various methods are employed to climb and harvest the fruits.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] In some regions in Thailand, locals make use of a bamboo ladder with natural step-like protrusions which in Thai known as *Phaong* (Thai: พะอง).
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] Harvesters use a vine to attach this bamboo ladder to the trunk, providing them with steps to climb up and reach the fruits.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] Some areas utilize hemp rope and slingshot.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] However, this method requires at least 2 people to collect the fruits as one of them must be responsible for climbing trees and harvesting the fruits, while the other stays on the ground to pull the climbing rope.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] During sap harvesting period, workers collect the sap twice a day, once in the morning and again in the evening.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] From a single tree, they typically obtain around 15-20 liters of fresh sap in each harvest.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] Bamboo tubes or plastic buckets are utilized to collect the dripping sap.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] In the Philippines, an annual Irok Festival is celebrated in the municipality of Indang in Cavite which is a major producer of kaong fruits, *sukang kaong*, and *tubâ* in the country.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] *Irok* is a local name for *Arenga pinnata* in the northwestern Philippines.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] The world's first ever crossword puzzle, labelled "Word-Cross" in the 21 December 1913 edition of *New York World* newspaper's Sunday *Fun* supplement and created by Arthur Wynne, a Liverpool, UK-born journalist, included a clue: *The fibre of the gomuti plant*.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] In some areas of southern Thailand, such as Ban Khlong Bor Saen and Bang Toei, Phang Nga, cultural beliefs associated with Arenga pinnata are prevalent.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] The trees are intertwined with the locals' lives and serve as a source of income for the villagers over generations.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] The locals typically call this plant *Chok* (Thai: ชก) or *Nao* (Thai: เหนา) .
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] However, it has a nickname "*Ton Luk Kha Mae"* (Thai: ต้นลูกฆ่าแม่) which means a child kills its mother, as the Arenga pinnata in those areas can produce fruits only once in its lifetime and it will perish within 4 -5 years.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] A belief revolves around the practice of singing and dancing during the sap tapping process.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] Locals believe that when the tree is surrounded by music, it yields abundantly and the sap quality is enhanced.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] While climbers harvest sap, some ground workers actively engage in singing and dancing.
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] Moreover, some locals have specific classifications for the female trees dividing them into three types, which are *Nao saw* (Thai: เหนาสาว), *Nao Mae Mai* (Thai: เหนาแม่ม่าย), and *Nao Kae* (Thai: เหนาแก่).
[src:arenga-pinnata/arenga-pinnata] The word “Nao” refers to the tree while each subsequent word provides a different meaning that signifies the duration the tree has been tapped for sap.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Asia shares the landmass of Eurasia with Europe, and of Afro-Eurasia with both Europe and Africa.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] In general terms, it is bounded on the east by the Pacific Ocean, on the south by the Indian Ocean, and on the north by the Arctic Ocean.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The border of Asia with Europe is a historical and cultural construct, as there is no clear physical and geographical separation between them.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] A commonly accepted division places Asia to the east of the Suez Canal separating it from Africa; and to the east of the Turkish straits, the Ural Mountains and Ural River, and to the south of the Caucasus Mountains and the Caspian and Black seas, separating it from Europe.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Since the concept of Asia derives from the term for the eastern region from a European perspective, Asia is the remaining vast area of Eurasia minus Europe.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Therefore, Asia is a region where various independent cultures coexist rather than sharing a single culture, and its boundary with Europe is somewhat arbitrary and has moved since its first conception in classical antiquity.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The division of Eurasia into two continents reflects East–West cultural differences, some of which vary on a spectrum.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] China and India traded places as the largest economies in the world from 1 to 1800 CE.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] China was a major economic power for much of recorded history, with the highest GDP per capita until 1500.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The Silk Road became the main east–west trading route in the Asian hinterlands while the Straits of Malacca stood as a major sea route.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Asia has exhibited economic dynamism as well as robust population growth during the 20th century, but overall population growth has since fallen.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Asia was the birthplace of most of the world's mainstream religions including Islam, Judaism, Christianity, Hinduism, Buddhism, and many other religions.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Asia varies greatly across and within its regions with regard to ethnic groups, cultures, environments, economics, historical ties, and government systems.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The term "Asia" is believed to originate in the Bronze Age toponym *Assuwa* (Hittite: 𒀸𒋗𒉿, romanized: *aš-šu-wa*) which originally referred only to a portion of northwestern Anatolia.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The term appears in Hittite records recounting how a confederation of Assuwan states including Troy unsuccessfully rebelled against the Hittite king Tudhaliya I around 1400 BCE.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Roughly contemporary Linear B documents contain the term *aswia* (Mycenaean Greek: 𐀀𐀯𐀹𐀊, romanized: *a-si-wi-ja*), seemingly in reference to captives from the same area.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Herodotus used the term in reference to Anatolia and the territory of the Achaemenid Empire, in contrast to Greece and Egypt.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] He reports that Greeks assumed that Asia was named after the wife of Prometheus, but that Lydians say it was named after *Asies*, son of Cotys, who passed the name on to a tribe at Sardis.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] In Greek mythology, "Asia" (Ἀσία or Ἀσίη) was the name of a "Nymph or Titan goddess of Lydia".
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The Iliad (attributed by the ancient Greeks to Homer) mentions two Phrygians in the Trojan War named Asios (literally 'Asian'); and also a marsh or lowland containing a marsh in Lydia as ασιος.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The term was later adopted by the Romans, who used it in reference to the province of Asia, located in western Anatolia.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] One of the first writers to use Asia as a name of the whole continent was Pliny.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The threefold division of the Old World into Africa, Asia, and Europe has been in use since the 6th century BCE, due to Greek geographers such as Anaximander and Hecataeus.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Anaximander placed the boundary between Asia and Europe along the Phasis River (now the Rioni) in Georgia of Caucasus (from its mouth by Poti on the Black Sea coast, through the Surami Pass and along the Kura River to the Caspian Sea), a convention still followed by Herodotus in the 5th century BCE.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] During the Hellenistic period, this convention was revised, and the boundary between Europe and Asia was now considered to be the Tanais (the modern Don River).
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] This is the convention used by Roman era authors such as Posidonius, Strabo and Ptolemy.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The border between Asia and Europe was later redefined by European academics.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] In 1730, five years after the death of Peter the Great, Philip Johan von Strahlenberg published in Sweden a new atlas proposing the Ural Mountains as the border of Asia.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Vasily Tatishchev announced that he had proposed the idea to von Strahlenberg.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The latter had suggested the Emba River as the southern part of this boundary.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Over the next century various proposals were made until the Ural River prevailed in the mid-19th century.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The border had been moved perforce from the Black Sea (the Romans' definition) to the Caspian Sea into which the Emba and Ural rivers project.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Between the Black Sea and the Caspian, the border is often placed along the crest of the Caucasus Mountains, although it is sometimes placed further north, on the Kuma–Manych Depression.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The boundary between Asia and Africa is the Suez Canal, the Gulf of Suez, the Red Sea, and the Bab-el-Mandeb.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] This makes Egypt a transcontinental country, with the Sinai Peninsula in Asia and the remainder of the country in Africa.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The border between Asia and Oceania is usually placed somewhere in the Indonesian Archipelago, specifically in Eastern Indonesia.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The Wallace Line separates the Asian and Wallacea biogeographical realms, a transition zone of deep water straits between the Asian and Australian continental shelves.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Weber's Line split the region in two with regard to the balance of fauna between Asian origin or Australo-Papuan origin.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Wallacea's eastern boundary with Sahul is represented by the Lydekker's Line.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The Maluku Islands (except the Aru Islands) are often considered to lie on the border of southeast Asia, with the Aru Islands and Western New Guinea, to the east of the Lydekker's Line, being wholly part of Oceania, as both lie on the Australian continental plate.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Culturally, the Wallacea region denoted the transition between Austronesian and Melanesian people, with varying degrees of intermixing between the two.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] In general, the further west and coastal a region is, the stronger the Austronesian influences, and the further east and inland a region is, the stronger the Melanesian influences.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The terms Southeast Asia and Oceania, devised in the 19th century, have had several vastly different geographic meanings since their inception.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The chief factor in determining which islands of the Indonesian Archipelago are Asian has been the location of the colonial possessions of the various empires there (not all European).
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The Bering Strait and Bering Sea separate the landmasses of Asia and North America, as well as forming the international boundary between Russia and the United States.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] This national and continental boundary separates the Diomede Islands in the Bering Strait, with Big Diomede in Russia and Little Diomede in the United States.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The Aleutian Islands are an island chain extending westward from the Alaskan Peninsula toward Russia's Komandorski Islands and Kamchatka Peninsula.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The Aleutian Islands are sometimes associated with Oceania, owing to their status as remote Pacific islands, and their proximity to the Pacific Plate.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] This is extremely rare however, due to their non-tropical biogeography, as well as their inhabitants, who have historically been related to the Indigenous peoples of the Americas.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Lawrence Island in the northern Bering Sea belongs to the US state of Alaska and may be associated with either continent but is almost always considered part of North America, as with the Rat Islands in the Aleutian chain.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] At their nearest points, Alaska and Russia are separated by only 4 kilometres (2.5 miles).
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Geographical Asia is a cultural artifact of European conceptions of the world, beginning with the Ancient Greeks, being imposed onto other cultures, an imprecise concept causing endemic contention about what it means.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Asia does not exactly correspond to the cultural borders of its various types of constituents.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] From the time of Herodotus, a minority of geographers have rejected the three-continent system (Europe, Africa, Asia) on the grounds that there is no substantial physical separation between them.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] For example, Sir Barry Cunliffe, the emeritus professor of European archeology at Oxford, argues that Europe has been geographically and culturally merely "the western excrescence of the continent of Asia".
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Geographically, Asia is the major eastern constituent of the continent of Eurasia with Europe being a northwestern peninsula of the landmass.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Asia, Europe and Africa make up a single continuous landmass—Afro-Eurasia—and share a common continental shelf.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Almost all of Europe and a major part of Asia sit atop the Eurasian Plate, adjoined on the south by the Arabian and Indian Plate and with the easternmost part of Siberia (east of the Chersky Range) on the North American Plate.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] About 1.8 million years ago, *Homo erectus* left the African continent.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] This species is believed to have lived in East and Southeast Asia from 1.8 million to 110,000 years ago.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Researchers believe that the modern human, or *Homo sapiens*, migrated about 60,000 years ago to South Asia along the Indian Ocean.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Modern humans interbred with an archaic human species called Denisovans in Southeast Asia.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Before the arrival of modern humans, Flores was occupied by *Homo floresiensis*, a small archaic human.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Ancestors of East Eurasians split from Ancient West Eurasians about 46,000 years ago, migrating out of the hub in the Iranian Plateau.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The history of Asia can be seen as the distinct histories of several peripheral coastal regions: East Asia, South Asia, Southeast Asia, Central Asia, and West Asia.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The coastal periphery was home to some of the world's earliest known civilisations, each of them developing around fertile river valleys.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The civilisations in Mesopotamia, the Indus Valley and the Yellow River shared many similarities.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] These civilisations may well have exchanged technologies and ideas such as mathematics and the wheel.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Other innovations, such as writing, seem to have been developed individually in each area.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Cities, states and empires developed in these lowlands.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The central steppe region had long been inhabited by horse-mounted nomads who could reach all areas of Asia from the steppes.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The earliest postulated expansion out of the steppe is that of the Indo-Europeans, who spread their languages into West Asia, South Asia, and the borders of China, where the Tocharians resided.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The northernmost part of Asia, including much of Siberia, was largely inaccessible to the steppe nomads, owing to the dense forests, climate and tundra.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] These areas remained very sparsely populated.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The center and the peripheries were mostly kept separated by mountains and deserts.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The Caucasus and Himalaya mountains and the Karakum and Gobi deserts formed barriers that the steppe horsemen could cross only with difficulty.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] While the urban city dwellers were more advanced technologically and socially, in many cases they could do little in a military aspect to defend against the mounted hordes of the steppe.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] However, the lowlands did not have enough open grasslands to support a large equestrian force; for this and other reasons, the nomads who conquered states in China, India, and the Middle East often found themselves adapting to the local, more affluent societies.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The Mongol Empire conquered a large part of Asia in the 13th century, an area extending from China to Europe.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Before the Mongol invasion, Song dynasty reportedly had approximately 120 million citizens; the 1300 census which followed the invasion reported roughly 60 million people.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The Black Death, one of the most devastating pandemics in human history, is thought to have originated in the arid plains of central Asia, where it then travelled along the Silk Road.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] European involvement in Asia became more significant from the Age of Discovery onward, with Iberian-sponsored sailors such as Christopher Columbus and Vasco da Gama paving the way for new routes from Atlantic Europe to Pacific Asia and the Indian Ocean respectively in the late 15th century.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The Russian Empire also began to expand into northwestern Asia from the 17th century, and would eventually take control of all of Siberia and most of Central Asia by the end of the 19th century.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Among non-European empires, the Ottoman Empire controlled Anatolia, most of the Middle East, North Africa and the Balkans from the mid 16th century onward, while in the 17th century, the Manchu conquered China and established the Qing dynasty.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The Islamic Mughal Empire (preceded by the Delhi Sultanate of the 13th to early 16th century) and the Hindu Maratha Empire controlled much of India in the 16th and 18th centuries respectively.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Western imperialism in Asia from the 18th to 20th centuries coincided with the Industrial Revolution in the West and the dethroning of India and China as the world's foremost economies.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Around this time, Western powers started to dominate China in what later became known as the century of humiliation, with the British-supported opium trade and later Opium Wars resulting in China being forced into an unprecedented situation of importing more than it exported.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] One significant influence on Japan had been the United States, which had begun projecting influence across the Pacific after its early-to-mid-19th century westward expansion.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The breakup of the Ottoman Empire in the early 20th century led to the Middle East also being contested and partitioned by the British and French.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] With the end of World War II in 1945 and the wartime ruination of Europe and imperial Japan, many countries in Asia were able to rapidly free themselves of colonial rule.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The independence of India came along with the carving out of a separate nation for the majority of South Asian Muslims, which in 1971 further split into Pakistan and Bangladesh; The Cold War in Asia strained relations between India and Pakistan and affected Asia more generally.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The end of the Cold War and the Soviet Union by 1991 saw the independence of the five modern Central Asian countries.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Some Arab countries took economic advantage of massive oil deposits that were discovered in their territory, becoming globally influential, though stability in the Middle East has been affected since 1948 by the Arab–Israeli conflict and American-led interventions.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] East Asian nations (along with Singapore in Southeast Asia) became economically prosperous with high-growth "tiger economies"; China, having undergone the reform and opening up under Deng Xiaoping, regained its place among the top two economies of the world by the 21st century.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] It covers 9% of the Earth's total surface area (or 30% of its land area), and has the longest coastline, at 62,800 kilometres (39,022 mi).
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Asia is generally defined as comprising the eastern four-fifths of Eurasia.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] It is located to the east of the Suez Canal and the Ural Mountains, and south of the Caucasus Mountains (or the Kuma–Manych Depression) and the Caspian and Black Seas.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] It is bounded on the east by the Pacific Ocean, on the south by the Indian Ocean and on the north by the Arctic Ocean.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Asia is subdivided into 49 countries, five of them (Georgia, Azerbaijan, Russia, Kazakhstan and Turkey) are transcontinental countries lying partly in Europe.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Geographically, Russia is partly and mostly in Asia, but is considered a European nation, both culturally and politically.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The Gobi Desert is in Mongolia and the Arabian Desert stretches across much of the Middle East.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The Yangtze in China is the longest river in the continent.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The Himalayas between Nepal and China is the tallest mountain range in the world.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Tropical rainforests stretch across much of southern Asia and coniferous and deciduous forests lie farther north.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Between 1990 and 2000 the area of primary forest in Asia decreased by 1.06 million hectares per year, between 2000 and 2015 it decreased by 280 000 ha per year.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] There are various approaches to the regional division of Asia.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The following subdivision into regions is used, among others, by the United Nations Statistics Division (UNSD).
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] This division of Asia into regions by the United Nations is done solely for statistical reasons and does not imply any assumption about political or other affiliations of countries and territories.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Asia has extremely diverse climate features.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Climates range from Arctic and subarctic in Siberia to tropical in southern India and Southeast Asia.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] It is moist across southeast sections, and dry across much of the interior.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Some of the largest daily temperature ranges on Earth occur in western sections of Asia.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The monsoon circulation dominates across southern and eastern sections, due to the presence of the Himalayas forcing the formation of a thermal low which draws in moisture during the summer.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Southwestern sections of the continent are hot.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Siberia is one of the coldest places in the Northern Hemisphere, and can act as a source of arctic air masses for North America.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The most active place on Earth for tropical cyclone activity lies northeast of the Philippines and south of Japan.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Climate change is particularly important in Asia, as the continent accounts for the majority of the human population.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Warming since the 20th century is increasing the threat of heatwaves across the entire continent.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Heatwaves lead to increased mortality, and the demand for air conditioning is rapidly accelerating as the result.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] By 2080, around 1 billion people in the cities of South and Southeast Asia are expected to experience around a month of extreme heat every year.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The impacts on water cycle are more complicated: already arid regions, primarily located in West Asia and Central Asia, will see more droughts, while areas of East, Southeast and South Asia which are already wet due to the monsoons will experience more flooding.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The waters around Asia are subjected to the same impacts as elsewhere, such as the increased warming and ocean acidification.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] There are many coral reefs in the region, and they are highly vulnerable to climate change, to the point practically all of them will be lost if the warming exceeds 1.5 °C (2.7 °F).
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Asia's distinctive mangrove ecosystems are also highly vulnerable to sea level rise.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Asia also has more countries with large coastal populations than any other continent, which would cause large economic impacts from sea level rise.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Water supplies in the Hindu Kush region will become more unstable as its enormous glaciers, known as the "Asian water towers", gradually melt.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] These changes to water cycle also affect vector-borne disease distribution, with malaria and dengue fever expected to become more prominent in the tropical and subtropical regions.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Food security will become more uneven, and South Asian countries could experience significant impacts from global food price volatility.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Historical emissions from Asia are lower than those from Europe and North America.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] However, China has been the single largest emitter of greenhouse gases in the 21st century, while India is the third-largest.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] As a whole, Asia currently accounts for 36% of world's primary energy consumption, which is expected to increase to 48% by 2050.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] By 2040, it is also expected to account for 80% of the world's coal and 26% of the world's natural gas consumption.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] While the United States remains the world's largest oil consumer, by 2050 it is projected to move to third place, behind China and India.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] While nearly half of the world's new renewable energy capacity is built in Asia, this is not yet sufficient in order to meet the goals of the Paris Agreement.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] They imply that the renewables would account for 35% of total energy consumption in Asia by 2030.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Climate change adaptation is already a reality for many Asian countries, with a wide range of strategies attempted across the continent.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Important examples include the growing implementation of climate-smart agriculture in certain countries or the "sponge city" planning principles in China.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] While some countries have drawn up extensive frameworks such as the Bangladesh Delta Plan or Japan's Climate Adaptation Act, others still rely on localized actions that are not effectively scaled up.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The most democratic countries in Asia are Japan, Taiwan and South Korea according to the V-Dem Democracy indices.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Within the states mentioned above are several partially recognized countries with limited to no international recognition.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Asia is both the largest continental economy in the world by both GDP nominal and PPP values and the world's fastest growing economic region.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] As of 2026, China is by far the largest economy on the continent.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] It is followed by India, Japan, South Korea, Turkey, Indonesia, Saudi Arabia, and Taiwan, which are all ranked among the top 20 largest economies by both nominal GDP and PPP values.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Based on Global Office Locations 2011, Asia dominated global office locations with 4 of the top 5 being in Asia: Hong Kong, Singapore, Tokyo and Seoul.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Around 68% of international firms have an office in Hong Kong.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] In the late 1990s and early 2000s, the economy of China had an average annual growth rate of more than 8%.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] According to economic historian Angus Maddison, India had the world's largest economy for much of the past three millennia prior to the 19th century, accounting for 25% of the world's industrial output.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] China was the largest and most advanced economy on Earth for much of recorded history and shared the mantle with India.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] For several decades in the late twentieth century, Japan was the largest economy in Asia and second-largest in the world, after surpassing the Soviet Union (measured in net material product) in 1990 and Germany in 1968.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] This ended in 2010, when China overtook Japan to become the world's second largest economy.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] In 2025, India overtook Japan in terms of nominal GDP to become the world's 4th largest and Asia's 2nd largest economy.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] In the late 1980s and early 1990s, Japan's GDP by currency exchange rates was almost as large as that of the rest of Asia combined.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] In 1995, Japan's economy nearly equaled that of the US as the largest economy in the world for a day, after the Japanese currency reached a record high of 79 yen/US$.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Economic growth in Asia since World War II to the 1990s had been concentrated in Japan as well as South Korea, Taiwan, Hong Kong, and Singapore, known as the Four Asian Tigers, which are now all considered developed economies, having among the highest GDP per capita in Asia.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Asia is the largest continent in the world by a considerable margin, and it is rich in natural resources, such as petroleum, forests, fish, water, rice, copper and silver.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Manufacturing in Asia has traditionally been strongest in East and Southeast Asia, particularly in China, Taiwan, South Korea, Japan, India, the Philippines, and Singapore.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Japan and South Korea continue to dominate in the area of multinational corporations, though increasingly China and India are making significant inroads.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Many companies from Europe, North America, South Korea, and Japan have operations in Asia's developing countries to take advantage of its abundant supply of cheap labour and relatively developed infrastructure.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] According to Citigroup in 2011, 9 of 11 Global Growth Generator countries came from Asia driven by population and income growth.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] They are Bangladesh, China, India, Indonesia, Iraq, Mongolia, the Philippines, Sri Lanka, and Vietnam.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Asia has three main financial centers: Hong Kong, Tokyo, and Singapore.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Call centers and business process outsourcing firms (BPOs) are becoming major employers in India and the Philippines due to the availability of a large pool of highly skilled, English-speaking workers.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The increased use of outsourcing has assisted the rise of India and the China as financial centers.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Due to its large and extremely competitive information technology industry, India has become a major hub for outsourcing.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Trade between Asian countries and countries on other continents is largely carried out via sea routes.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] A far smaller part of the goods traffic runs via South Africa to Europe.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] A particularly significant part of Asian goods traffic is carried out on the Pacific Rim, toward Los Angeles and Long Beach.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The melting of the Arctic is also paving the way for new shipping routes from Northeast Asia to Europe and North America.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The land route to Europe is also the subject of construction projects, comparatively smaller in scope.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Intra-Asian trade, including sea trade, is growing rapidly.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] In 2010, Asia had 3.3 million millionaires (people with net worth over US$1 million excluding their homes), slightly below North America's 3.4 million.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] In 2011, Asia topped Europe in the number of millionaires.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Citigroup in The Wealth Report 2012 stated that the total wealth of people in Asia with over $100 million in assets exceeded that of their North American counterparts for the first time, as the world's "economic center of gravity" continued moving east.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] At the end of 2011, there were 18,000 people in Asia, mainly in Southeast Asia, China, and Japan, with at least $100 million in disposable assets, compared to North America with 17,000 and Western Europe with 14,000.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Asia's electricity demand has quadrupled since 2000 (rising from 4,199 TWh to over 16,000 TWh in 2024).
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] This growth, driven largely by China and increasingly by India, Indonesia, and Viet Nam, makes Asia the fastest-growing region for electricity demand globally, at about 5% per year.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] The region now accounts for about 36% of global primary energy consumption, a share projected to approach 50% by 2050.: 1468 Fossil fuels remain central in Asia: 66% of its energy is generated from fossil fuels, and Asia makes up 83% of the world's coal generation.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] However, coal is slowly being phased out and natural gas is displacing oil and oil products in various sectors, supported by policies and regulations.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] Natural gas demand in emerging market and developing economies in Asia expanded by around 6% in 2024, accounting for nearly 40% of incremental global gas demand.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] At the same time, Asia is the global leader in renewable energy expansion.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] It is currently the only region on track to meet the goal of tripling renewable capacity by 2030, largely due to China, the leading nation in renewable energy generation.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] China's wind and solar capacity has surged in recent years, together overtaking that of coal, while in 2024 India become the world's third largest generator of electricity from wind and solar.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] In 2013, with regional tourism growing and dominated by Chinese visitors, MasterCard released the Global Destination Cities Index report, in which 10 of 20 cities are Asian and Pacific cities.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p01] This was also the first time an Asian city (Bangkok) was in the number one spot, with 15.98 million international visitors.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] East Asia had by far the strongest overall Human Development Index (HDI) improvement of any region in the world, nearly doubling average HDI attainment over the past 40 years, according to the report's analysis of health, education and income data.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] China, the second highest achiever in the world in terms of HDI improvement since 1970, is the only country on the "Top 10 Movers" list due to income rather than health or education achievements.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Its per capita income increased a stunning 21-fold over the last four decades, also lifting hundreds of millions out of income poverty.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Yet it was not among the region's top performers in improving school enrollment and life expectancy.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Nepal, a South Asian country, emerges as one of the world's fastest movers since 1970 mainly due to health and education achievements.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Its present life expectancy is 25 years longer than in the 1970s.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] More than four of every five children of school age in Nepal now attend primary school, compared to just one in five 40 years ago.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Hong Kong ranked highest among the countries grouped on the HDI (number 7 in the world, which is in the "very high human development" category), followed by Singapore (9), Japan (19) and South Korea (22).
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Afghanistan (155) ranked lowest amongst Asian countries out of the 169 countries assessed.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Asia is home to several language families and many language isolates.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Most Asian countries have more than one language that is natively spoken.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] For instance, according to Ethnologue, more than 700 languages are spoken in Indonesia, more than 400 languages spoken in India, and more than 100 are spoken in the Philippines.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] China has many languages and dialects in different provinces.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Many of the world's major religions have their origins in Asia, including the five most practiced in the world (excluding irreligion), which are Christianity, Islam, Hinduism, Chinese folk religion (classified as Confucianism and Taoism), and Buddhism.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] The story of the Great Flood for example, as presented to Jews in the Hebrew Bible in the narrative of Noah—and later to Christians in the Old Testament, and to Muslims in the Quran—is earliest found in Mesopotamian mythology, in the Enûma Eliš and *Epic of Gilgamesh*.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Hindu mythology similarly tells about an avatar of Vishnu in the form of a fish who warned Manu of a terrible flood.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Ancient Chinese mythology also tells of a Great Flood spanning generations, one that required the combined efforts of emperors and divinities to control.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] The Abrahamic religions including Judaism, Christianity, Islam, Druze faith, and Baháʼí Faith originated in West Asia.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Jews are the predominant ethnic group in Israel (75.6%) numbering at about 6.1 million, although the levels of adherence to Jewish religion vary.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Outside of Israel there are small ancient Jewish communities in Turkey (17,400), Azerbaijan (9,100), Iran (8,756), India (5,000) and Uzbekistan (4,000), among many other places.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] As of 2016, there are am estimated 14.4–17.5 million (2016, est.) Jews alive in the world today, making them one of the smallest Asian minorities, at roughly 0.3–0.4& of the total population of the continent.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Christianity is a widespread religion in Asia, with more than 286 million adherents in 2010 according to Pew Research Center, and nearly 364 million according to Britannica Book of the Year 2014.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Christians constitute around 12.6% of the total population of Asia.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] In the Philippines and Timor-Leste, Catholicism is the predominant religion; it was introduced by the Spaniards and the Portuguese, respectively.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] In Armenia and Georgia, Eastern Orthodoxy is the predominant religion.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] In the Middle East, such as in the Levant, Anatolia and Fars, Syriac Christianity (Church of the East) and Oriental Orthodoxy are prevalent minority denominations, which are both Eastern Christian sects mainly adhered to Assyrian people or Syriac Christians.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Vibrant indigenous minorities in West Asia are adhering to the Eastern Catholic Churches and Eastern Orthodoxy.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Saint Thomas Christians in India trace their origins to the evangelistic activity of Thomas the Apostle in the 1st century.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Significant Christian communities also found in Central Asia, South Asia, Southeast Asia and East Asia.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Islam, which originated in the Hejaz located in modern-day Saudi Arabia, is the second largest and most widely-spread religion in Asia with at least 1 billion Muslims constituting around 23.8% of the total population of Asia.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] With 12.7% of the world Muslim population, the country currently with the largest Muslim population in the world is Indonesia, followed by Pakistan (11.5%), India (10%), Bangladesh, Iran and Turkey.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Mecca, Medina and Jerusalem are the three holiest cities for Islam in all the world.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] The Hajj and Umrah attract large numbers of Muslim devotees from all over the world to Mecca and Medina.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] The Druze originated in West Asia, is a monotheistic religion based on the teachings of figures like Hamza ibn Ali and al-Hakim bi-Amr Allah, and Greek philosophers such as Plato and Aristotle.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] The number of Druze people worldwide is around one million.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Around 45–50% live in Syria, 35% to 40% live in Lebanon, and less than 10% live in Israel.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Recently there has been a growing Druze diaspora.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] The Baháʼí Faith originated in Asia, in Iran (Persia), and spread from there to the Ottoman Empire, Central Asia, India, and Burma during the lifetime of Bahá'u'lláh.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Since the middle of the 20th century, growth has particularly occurred in other Asian countries, because Baháʼí activities in many Muslim countries has been severely suppressed by authorities.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Lotus Temple is a big Baháʼí temple in India.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Almost all Asian religions have philosophical character and Asian philosophical traditions cover a large spectrum of philosophical thoughts and writings.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Indian philosophy includes Hindu philosophy and Buddhist philosophy.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] They include elements of nonmaterial pursuits, whereas another school of thought from India, Cārvāka, preached the enjoyment of the material world.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] The religions of Hinduism, Buddhism, Jainism and Sikhism originated in India, South Asia.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] In East Asia, particularly in China and Japan, Confucianism, Taoism and Zen Buddhism took shape.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] As of 2012, Hinduism has around 1.1 billion adherents.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] The faith represents around 25% of Asia's population and is the largest religion in Asia.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] However, it is mostly concentrated in South Asia.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Over 80% of the populations of both India and Nepal adhere to Hinduism, alongside significant communities in Bangladesh, Pakistan, Bhutan, Sri Lanka and Bali, Indonesia.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Many overseas Indians in countries such as Burma, Singapore and Malaysia also adhere to Hinduism.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Buddhism has a great following in Mainland Southeast Asia and East Asia.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] The Communist-governed countries of China, Vietnam and North Korea are officially atheist, thus the number of Buddhists and other religious adherents may be under-reported.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Jainism is found mainly in India and in overseas Indian communities such as the United States and Malaysia.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Sikhism is found in Northern India and amongst overseas Indian communities in other parts of Asia, especially Southeast Asia.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Confucianism is found predominantly in mainland China, South Korea, Taiwan and in overseas Chinese populations.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Taoism is found mainly in mainland China, Taiwan, Malaysia and Singapore.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] In many Chinese communities, Taoism is easily syncretised with Mahayana Buddhism, thus exact religious statistics are difficult to obtain and may be understated or overstated.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] The culture of Asia is a diverse blend of customs and traditions that have been practiced by the various ethnic groups of the continent for centuries.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] The continent is divided into six geographic sub-regions: Central Asia, East Asia, North Asia, South Asia, Southeast Asia, and West Asia.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] These regions are defined by their cultural similarities, including common religions, languages, and ethnicities.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] West Asia, also known as Southwest Asia or the Middle East, has cultural roots in the ancient civilisations of the Fertile Crescent and Mesopotamia, which gave rise to the Persian, Arab, Ottoman empires, as well as the Abrahamic religions of Judaism, Christianity and Islam.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] These civilisations, which are located in the Hilly flanks, are among the oldest in the world, with evidence of farming dating back to around 9000 BCE.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Despite the challenges posed by the vast size of the continent and the presence of natural barriers such as deserts and mountain ranges, trade and commerce have helped to create a Pan-Asian culture that is shared across the region.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Rabindranath Tagore, a Bengali dramatist and author from Santiniketan (now in West Bengal, India), won the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1913, becoming the first Asian Nobel laureate.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] The prize was awarded for Tagore's prose works and poetry, which had a significant additional impact on national literatures throughout the Western world.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Tagore also authored both the Indian and Bangladeshi national anthems.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Other Asian writers who won Nobel Prize for literature include Yasunari Kawabata (Japan, 1968), Kenzaburō Ōe (Japan, 1994), Gao Xingjian (China, 2000), Orhan Pamuk (Turkey, 2006), Mo Yan (China, 2012), and Han Kang (South Korea, 2024).
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Some may consider the American writer, Pearl S.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Mother Teresa of India and Shirin Ebadi of Iran were awarded the Nobel Peace Prize for their significant and pioneering efforts for democracy and human rights, especially for the rights of women and children.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Ebadi is the first Iranian and the first Muslim woman to receive the prize.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Another Nobel Peace Prize winner is Aung San Suu Kyi from Burma for her peaceful and non-violent struggle under a military dictatorship in Burma.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] She is a nonviolent pro-democracy activist and leader of the National League for Democracy in Burma (Myanmar) and a noted prisoner of conscience.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] She is a Buddhist and was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1991.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Chinese dissident Liu Xiaobo was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize for "his long and non-violent struggle for fundamental human rights in China" on 8 October 2010.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] He is the first Chinese citizen to be awarded a Nobel Prize of any kind while residing in China.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] In 2014, Kailash Satyarthi from India and Malala Yousafzai from Pakistan were awarded the Nobel Peace Prize "for their struggle against the suppression of children and young people and for the right of all children to education".
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Raman is the first Asian to get a Nobel prize in Sciences.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] He won the Nobel Prize in Physics "for his work on the scattering of light and for the discovery of the effect named after him".
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Japan has won the most Nobel Prizes of any Asian nation with 24 followed by India which has won 13.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] 1933) is an Indian economist who was awarded the 1998 Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences for his contributions to welfare economics and social choice theory, and for his interest in the problems of society's poorest members.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Most of the said awardees are from Japan and Israel except for Chandrasekhar and Raman (India), Abdus Salam (Pakistan), Arafat (Palestinian Territories), Kim (South Korea), and Horta and Belo (Timor-Leste).
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] In 2006, the Bangladeshi Muhammad Yunus of was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize for the establishment of Grameen Bank, a community development bank that lends money to poor people, especially women.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] He is known for the concept of micro credit which, allows poor and destitute people to borrow money.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] The borrowers pay back money within the specified period and defaulting is very low.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] Yunus also became the leader of an interim government after the 2024 Bangladesh quota reform movement.
[src:arenga-pinnata/asia-p02] The Dalai Lama received the Nobel Peace Prize, in Oslo, Norway in 1989.
[src:arenga-pinnata/atlantic-books] CEO Toby Mundy was listed by the *Evening Standard* as one of London's top 1000 most influential people in 2012.
[src:arenga-pinnata/atlantic-books] Atlantic Books was founded in February 2000 by Toby Mundy.
[src:arenga-pinnata/atlantic-books] It was originally the UK subsidiary of the American independent publisher Grove/Atlantic Inc.
[src:arenga-pinnata/atlantic-books] Grove/Atlantic sold a majority stake in the company in 2009.
[src:arenga-pinnata/atlantic-books] Allen & Unwin became the majority owner in 2014.
[src:arenga-pinnata/atlantic-books] In 2010, Atlantic Books launched a new genre fiction imprint, Corvus, introducing the world of crime, fantasy historical and women's fiction, into the company's list.
[src:arenga-pinnata/atlantic-books] Corvus is home to the Douglas Brodie crime novels by Gordon Ferris, the *Merrily Watkins Mysteries* by Phil Rickman, and the *Vespasian* series written by Robert Fabbri.
[src:arenga-pinnata/atlantic-books] Other authors include Holly Seddon, Caroline Bond, Sanjida Kay, Jack Jordan, and Jacqueline Ward.
[src:arenga-pinnata/atlantic-books] In 2013, *Dark Eden* by Chris Beckett, published by Corvus, won the Arthur C.
[src:arenga-pinnata/atlantic-books] Clarke Award – the most prestigious award for Science Fiction in Britain.
[src:arenga-pinnata/atlantic-books] Willow Wilson won the World Fantasy Award for Best Novel.
[src:arenga-pinnata/atlantic-books] In 2019, it was announced that editorial director, Sara O'Keeffe, was leaving the company.
[src:arenga-pinnata/atlantic-books] O'Keeffe had led the imprint for eight years, presiding over a number of successful publications, including Holly Seddon's debut break-out bestseller *Try Not To Breathe* and Megan Miranda's *All The Missing Girls*.
[src:arenga-pinnata/atlantic-books] O'Keeffe was also responsible for attracting established names including Minette Walters and Elizabeth Buchan.
[src:arenga-pinnata/atlantic-books] Sarah Hodgson, formerly deputy publishing director at HarperCollins, replaced O'Keeffe.
[src:arenga-pinnata/atlantic-books] Atlantic Books is a founding member of the Independent Alliance, a global alliance of ten UK publishers and their international partners, when it was formed by Faber and Faber in 2005.
[src:arenga-pinnata/atlantic-books] In 2009, Atlantic Books entered into a partnership with independent Australian publishers Allen & Unwin, enabling them to introduce their own titles to the Australian market and also to publish a few select Allen & Unwin titles in the UK.
